issue.title: Fix/timeout middleware not enforced
issue.body:
# Description

This PR refactors the timeout middleware to properly enforce request timeouts by:

1. Wrapping the handler execution in a goroutine.
2 Using a `select` statement to handle three possible outcomes:

    - Handler completes successfully.
    - Handler panics (panic is propagated).
    - Timeout occurs, triggering cfg.OnTimeout if set, or returning fiber.ErrRequestTimeout.. 


This change guarantees that:
- The timeout is respected in real time.
- Handlers have the opportunity to observe context cancellation if needed.
- Panics are safely propagated without losing stack traces.


Fixes #3671


## Changes introduced

- [ ] Benchmarks: Describe any performance benchmarks and improvements related to the changes.
- [ ] Documentation Update: Detail the updates made to the documentation and links to the changed files.

- [ ] Migration Guide: If necessary, provide a guide or steps for users to migrate their existing code to accommodate these changes.
- [ ] API Alignment with Express: Explain how the changes align with the Express API.
- [ ] API Longevity: Discuss the steps taken to ensure that the new or updated APIs are consistent and not prone to breaking changes.
- [ ] Examples: Provide examples demonstrating the new features or changes in action.

- [ ] Code consistency (non-breaking change which improves code reliability and robustness)

Please use emojis in commit messages for an easy way to identify the purpose or intention of a commit. Check out the emoji cheatsheet here: [CONTRIBUTING.md](https://github.com/gofiber/fiber/blob/main/.github/CONTRIBUTING.md#pull-requests-or-commits)

pull_request.title: Make Pow type-agnostic and move it back to numerics
pull_request.body:
This makes the generators in quantities/generators.hpp specific to the definition of operations on Quantity that correspond to predefined operations. When we introduce our own functions that work on Quantity and other things (e.g., `Pow`), we put that in `numerics` (why would `Pow` on a boost multiprecision type live in `quantities`?).

`Exponentiation` works like `Product` and does not know anything about how `Quantity` works (and thus likewise for `Derivatives` etc.).
`Pow` returns an `Exponentiation` and thus does not need to know anything about how `Quantity` works (just like other templatized numerics, e.g., `DoublePrecision`.

The headers that define constants depend on numerics::elementary_functions.

pull_request.title: Feat(paladin) configurable â€œsanctuary vs kingsâ€ policy on tanks + safe targeting
pull_request.body:
Ok Guys tis @/!%** Paladin  is driving me crazy!

### Summary

This PR introduces a configurable policy to prefer Blessing of Sanctuary over Blessing of Kings on tanks, and hardens the casting logic so Kings wonâ€™t overwrite Sanctuary (and vice-versa). 
In WotLK, Sanctuary provides 3% damage reduction and returns resources on avoidance, making it a strong tank blessing; Kings remains a universal fallback. 


### Why

- Many groups want Sanctuary on tanks (mitigation + resource return), Kings for everyone else. Playerbots previously defaulted to Kings in some paths or kept Sanctuary from replacing Kings immediately.
- I also ensure the â€œone Paladin blessing per targetâ€ rule is respected by preventing accidental overwrites. 


### What changed

1. New policy switch

- AiPlayerbot.Paladin.SanctuaryPriority (default 1)

- 1 => Prefer Sanctuary on tanks (if learned), Kings elsewhere.
- 0 => Prefer Kings; the Sanctuary action wonâ€™t auto-apply.

2. Sanctuary action is â€œstrictâ€

- The Sanctuary action never falls back to Kings. If the target isnâ€™t a tank (or the spell isnâ€™t known), it does nothing and lets the Kings action handle the rest.

3. Allow replacement when prioritized

- When SanctuaryPriority=1, the Sanctuary action targets party/raid members missing Sanctuary only, even if they already have Kings, so the tank gets Sanctuary immediately (Kings => Sanctuary upgrade).

4. Kings wonâ€™t overwrite Sanctuary

- The Kings actionâ€™s target filter now excludes Sanctuary (mono + greater), preventing Kings from replacing an already-applied Sanctuary.

5. Main-Tank focus for fast application

- If SanctuaryPriority=1 and the Main Tank lacks Sanctuary, the Sanctuary action forces its target to the MT before casting. This avoids selector ordering issues (master/healer first) and guarantees prompt application to the tank.


### Configuration
```
# Paladin â€” Sanctuary policy on tanks
# 1 = Sanctuary on tanks if learned (fallback Kings)
# 0 = Kings has priority; Sanctuary is not used automatically
# Default: 1
AiPlayerbot.Paladin.SanctuaryPriority = 1
```
Works alongside Strict Role Mode (OFF/ON/AUTO) and Greater/Single upgrade logic; no change required to existing settings.


### Implementation notes:

**Selector changes : **

**Sanctuary GetTargetValue():**

- Priority ON => match  without Sanctuary  (allows replacing Kings).
- Priority OFF => legacy behavior (requires neither Kings nor Sanctuary).

**Kings GetTargetValue() now excludes both Kings and Sanctuary.**

**Decision function**

- GetActualBlessingOfSanctuary(...) returns Sanctuary only for tanks (or the explicit Main Tank), otherwise empty (no cast). No implicit Kings fallback here.

**Execute path**

**Sanctuary Execute(...) optionally retargets the Main Tank if he lacks Sanctuary, then applies normal Greater vs Single upgrade with reagent handling.**


### Acceptance tests

**Default (priority=1)**

**Group with Prot Paladin (bstats), Warrior Prot, others:**

- Everyone receives Kings (Greater when appropriate).
- Warrior Protâ€™s Kings is immediately replaced by Sanctuary.
- Subsequent Kings passes do not overwrite Sanctuary.


**Priority=0**

- Same setup: tanks receive Kings; Sanctuary is not applied automatically.


**No Sanctuary learned**

- Priority=1 or 0: Kings behavior unchanged; no Sanctuary attempts.


### Backward compatibility

- Default is priority=1, which aligns with common WotLK tank buff practice (Sanctuary on tanks; Kings elsewhere). No behavior change for non-tank targets. The change is localized and low-risk.


**Why Sanctuary?**

- Greater Blessing of Sanctuary on WotLK: 3% damage taken reduction; +10% Strength/Stamina; returns mana/rage/runic power on block/parry/dodge. 
- Greater Blessing of Kings (WotLK): +10% stats; only one Paladin blessing per target at a time. 

Thanks for reviewing and tests.

Thanks

commits.message: Update .gitignore to streamline ignored files: removed unnecessary entries for PnP and coverage, adjusted local environment file patterns, and added support for pnpm debug logs.

Refactor conversation page to integrate conversationAPI for generating and regenerating replies. Removed hardcoded reply options and improved error handling for API calls. Updated event handling for message input and adjusted UI elements for clarity.
Collapse Information section when Generate Reply is clicked and remove redundant reply index display in conversation page.
Add profile analysis feature to Pickup Lines page, including state management and UI updates for displaying results. Remove Upload page as it is no longer needed.

Refactor profile analysis logic in API route and enhance Pickup Lines page to display analysis results. Integrate new service for profile analysis and improve state management for displaying insights and summary.

Update upload functionality to use screenshot upload instead of file upload. Modify links and button text across the application to reflect this change. Introduce new API methods for analyzing and generating responses from screenshots.
Refactor profile analysis response handling in API to enforce type safety by adding explicit type annotations for line filtering functions.

Refactor API structure by removing deprecated conversation and profile analysis services. Introduce a new client API for streamlined interactions with backend services. Update related components to utilize the new client API, enhancing maintainability and type safety across the application.

Add comprehensive error handling and logging system

- Introduced a new error handling system with custom error types for better categorization and management of errors.
- Implemented a logging system that supports multiple log levels and structured logging for improved traceability.
- Updated API routes to utilize the new error handling and logging mechanisms, enhancing robustness and maintainability.
- Added an ErrorBoundary component for React to catch and handle errors in the UI gracefully.
- Integrated error handling in client API requests to provide detailed feedback on failures.
- Enhanced the conversation and screenshot analysis APIs with validation and logging for better performance tracking.

Update terminology from "Smart Icebreakers" to "AI Pickup Lines" across the application, including README, UI components, and API handling. Adjusted related text for consistency and clarity, and modified profile analysis request structure to include \'bio\' and \'photos\' fields.

Refactor Pickup Lines API request structure to encapsulate summary and insights within an analysis object. Update related type definitions and enhance profile analysis prompt to prioritize text content extraction. This change improves data organization and clarity in API interactions.

Update metadata and add Google Analytics script across multiple pages

- Enhanced metadata for the layout, conversation, pickup lines, and upload screenshot pages to improve SEO and user engagement.
- Added Google Analytics tracking script to the layout for better performance monitoring and user behavior analysis.

labels.name: release-note-none
labels.description: Denotes a PR that doesn't merit a release note.

labels.name: dco-signoff: yes
labels.description: Indicates the PR's author has DCO signed all their commits.

issue.body:
**What this PR does / why we need it**:
The nightly build fails from time to time on unit tests, when trying to create dashboard handlers based on a non-exists directory of dashboard yamls.

The directory name is computed with:
```go
dir := path.Join(os.TempDir(), fmt.Sprint(time.Now().UTC().Unix()))
```

This pattern is used in two additional unit tests. The guess is that the directory is aleady exist, when the tests assumes it isn't.

This commit gives a unique directory name for each one of the tests that uses the temp directory name pattern, to ensure each test is using its own directory. Also, try to make these test more robust, by taking logic out of the `By` functions, and by adding some error checks.

**Release note**:
```release-note
None
```

issue.title: Resolve surrogate pairs in incoming mails
issue.body:
Sometimes MIME parts of incoming mails, that are declared to be encoded in UTF-8, contain surrogate pairs. A surrogate pair is a sequence of two invalid code points. These invalid code points constitute in UTF-16 a codepoint that lies outside the basic multilingual plane, that can't be represented in UTF-16 with two bytes. This effect was noticed when PostgreSQL refused to store CESU-8 in an UTF-8 database field.

An example is ` =ED=A0=BD=ED=B8=80` which indicate six bytes in quoted-printable encoding. These six bytes encode in UTF-8 the two invalid code points  0xD83D and 0xDE00. In UTF-16 these two invalid code points make up  `ðŸ˜€ - U+1F600 - F0 9F 98 80 - GRINNING FACE`. This funny encoding is called CESU-8 and can result from a sloppy conversion of UTF-16 to UTF-8.

See also the discussion in http://www.perl-community.de/bat/poard/thread/21688 .

These surrogate pairs can be resolved into valid Unicode with a Regexp substitution, see https://stackoverflow.com/questions/72553544/how-to-use-perl-pack-to-convert-utf-16-surrogate-pairs-to-utf-8 . Thanks to rosti at  http://www.perl-community.de  for finding this.

TODO:

- [ ] investigate where the resolution is best implemented
- [ ] add test cases
- [ ] resolve the surrogate pairs before storing the body in the database or in the file system.
